Iris Dataset

Generated by a biologist Ronald Fisher in 1936.

Iris Data

The data set consists of 50 samples from each of three species of Iris:

  • Iris setosa
  • Iris virginica
  • Iris versicolor

Four features were measured from each sample:

the length and the width of the sepals and petals, in centimeters.

Iris data.frame (Tidy / Long)

## [row, column]

## Single element. Second row and third column
## Result will be a scalar

Subset a dataframe: Column

## Single column. Third column
## Result will be a vector

## By name
## Result will be a vector

NOTE: Subsetting by name is specific to column. Does not work with row

Evaluate a characteristic

## Get proportion of each species with Sepal.Width > 3
table(iris[iris$Sepal.Width > 3, ]$Species)


    setosa versicolor  virginica 
        42          8         17

Pie chart

## Pie chart for plants with Sepal.Width > 3
pie(table(iris[iris$Sepal.Width > 3, ]$Species))

Statistical analysis: Anova

## Fit a model
iris.aov <- aov(Petal.Width ~ Species, data = iris)
summary(iris.aov)

Advantage of Long Format

Plotting your experiment

Experiment <- data.frame(Cells = c(3, 5, 6, 10, 12, 15, 17, 19),
                         Treatment = c(rep("Control", 3), rep("Drug", 5)))

boxplot(Cells ~ Treatment, data = Experiment)

Analysis of your experiment

## t-test
t.test(Cells ~ Treatment, data = Experiment)


    Welch Two Sample t-test

data:  Cells by Treatment
t = -5.3574, df = 5.7056, p-value = 0.002029
alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
95 percent confidence interval:
 -14.527576  -5.339091
sample estimates:
mean in group Control    mean in group Drug 
             4.666667             14.600000

Summary

  • Data Frame is powerful data structure in R

  • Data Frame is 2-D

    • Columns correspond to one feature (characteristic)
    • Row correspond to one case (sample)

  • Subsetting is [row, column] (can be number or name or conditional)

    • Special case: df$column

  • Qualitative Features are treated as Factors (Groups)

  • Formula (Quantitative ~ Qualitative) allow comparisons between groups
